snippet.textDisplay:
I love this. It shines a light that these are real people and real communities. I was with a gang member for about a decade and had his kids. I was a white suburban girl (like I lived under the poverty line but I was living with some people in the nice middle class suburbs) that got tied up with gangbangers and even though it ended badly and I'm happy its over, I'm also really hapoy that it happened. I met a lot of wonderful humans who would do anything, ANYTHING for the ones they hold dear. Gang culture is so deeply inbeded in the community. It's not the stereotypes we see on tv. It's people who are going to protect what they have and those they love at all costs. Honestly I've gained a lot of respect for gang culture through my experiences. I won't fetishize it or turn it into some fantasy because there are a lot of parts I really dont like as well. I'm not gunna get into that on this comment though.
I just wish we as a society weren't so quick to demonize people. I'm grateful I've gotten to live a lot of different lifestyles because its shown me we're all just humans who want the best possible outcome for ourselves and our families. And even though we go through different struggles, the human struggle is universal and we can at least all relate on that level.

Also
ACAB. The police are the country's biggest and most dangerous gang that are government funded and no one can change my mind. They're not included in anything I said above.

snippet.textDisplay:
I studied conflict at university. All over the world, crime thrives when you have poverty, oppression or any other type of societal problem. In the Americas it's gangs. In the Islamic world, it's "religious extremism". In Africa, it's localized militant groups or street gangs. Gangs are an example of a way for people at the bottom, who are poor, or who have been marginalized or forgotten, to do something, to say fuck the laws, fuck everybody on top, we're gonna do it our own way and not let them tell us how to act. The more violent side of it comes from the mental health issues and continuous trauma of living in a off the hook environment and from the anger of being put in that situation in the first place.


Sometimes, outside of America mostly, political opposition takes the form of more extremist groups that will be labeled gangs or terrorists and people will say how that proves that political ideology is wrong. The truth is, it's like that because of the conditions, not because of anything inherent to the ideology, or to the group that partakes in crime. People on top also commit crimes but the media doesn't demonize it like they do this stuff.
